            <pb n="2" facs="#f0001"/>
            <div n="1">
                <head>SCIENCE AND POETRY</head>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p><hi rendition="#k">I cannot</hi> yield any place in my mind to<lb break="yes"
                    />the solicitude which a certain narrowness of<lb break="yes"/>understanding and
                    a kind of sentimental<lb break="yes"/>dulness, have, in some instances led to,
                        that<lb break="yes"/>nature loses aught of her magic&#x2014;of her<lb
                        break="yes"/>charm of mysteriousness and grandeur&#x2014;by<lb break="yes"
                    />inquiries into the intimate constitution of her<lb break="yes"/>forces. The
                    natural philosopher, who, like<lb break="yes"/>Young, and Arago, and Fresnel,
                    measures the<lb break="yes"/>undulations, whose interferences strengthen<lb
                        break="yes"/>or weaken the ray of light; the astronomer,<lb break="yes"
                    />who, by the sky-piercing power of his tele-<lb break="no"/>scope, studies the
                    satellites of Uranus on the<lb break="yes"/>outermost verge of our system, or,
                    like Her-<lb break="no"/>shell, detects glimmering points of brighter<lb
                        break="yes"/>light in the coloured double stars, the<lb break="yes"
                    />botanist, whose initiated eye perceives the<lb break="yes"/>cumulation of the
                    sap-globules in the cells of<lb break="yes"/>the Charas, and who finds unity of
                        formation<lb break="yes"/>in species and natural families&#x2014;these
                        culti-<lb break="no"/>vated intellects surely look into the depths<lb
                        break="yes"/>of heaven, and survey the flower-clad surface<lb break="yes"
                    />of the earth with a grander eye than the ob-<lb break="no"/>server, whose
                    intellectual vision is not yet<lb break="yes"/>sharpened by any apprehension of
                    the en-<lb break="no"/>chainent of phenomena. Whilst vulgar<lb break="yes"
                    />sense conceives the stars to be inlaid in a<lb break="yes"/>crystalline vault,
                    the astronomer actually ex-<lb break="no"/>tends the bounds of space, for if he
                        circum-<lb break="no"/>scribes the cluster of stars, of which our sun<lb
                        break="yes"/>is one, it is only that he may show others<lb break="yes"/>and
                    others, a countless multitude of groups<lb break="yes"/>of suns&#x2014;the
                    infinite depths of space, till<lb break="yes"/>vision fails, still studded with
                    astral systems<lb break="yes"/>like our own. The feeling of the sublime, in<lb
                        break="yes"/>so far as it seems to spring from the simple<lb break="yes"
                    />contemplation of infinite space, is closely al-<lb break="no"/>lied to that
                    wrapt mood of the mind which,<lb break="yes"/>in the realm of the spiritual, in
                    abstract con-<lb break="no"/>verse with our own consciousness, arises from<lb
                        break="yes"/>the meditation of the endless and the free.<lb break="yes"
                    />Upon this affinity, this relationship of sensu-<lb break="no"/>ous
                    impressions, depends the magic, the feel-<lb break="no"/>ing of infinitude,
                    which we experience when<lb break="yes"/>we are gazing over the shoreless ocean,
                        sur-<lb break="no"/>rounding some isolated mountain-peak, or<lb break="yes"
                    />are penetrating the depths of heavenly space<lb break="yes"/>with the
                    telescope, and resolving nebulous<lb break="yes"/>specks into their constituent
                    stars. Let<lb break="yes"/>him, therefore, whom circumstances permit<lb
                        break="yes"/>to escape from time to time from the narrow<lb break="yes"
                    />circle of his every-day occupations, lament<lb break="yes"/>that he has
                    &#x201C;remained so long a stranger to<lb break="yes"/>nature, unconscious of
                    her charms,&#x201D; and learn<lb break="yes"/>that in the contemplation of her
                        grandeur<lb break="yes"/>and freedom, there dwells the purest delight<lb
                        break="yes"/>which exalted intelligence can obtain for man.<lb break="yes"
                    />The study of general natural science, indeed,<lb break="yes"/>awakens organs
                    in our interior, that have long<lb break="yes"/>slumbered. We enter upon a new
                    and more<lb break="yes"/>intimate intercourse with the external world,<lb
                        break="yes"/>and are brought to feel a larger sympathy<lb break="yes"/>with
                    that which proclaims at once the indus-<lb break="no"/>trial progress and the
                    intellectual improve-<lb break="no"/>ment of mankind.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>
                        <hi rendition="#et">
                            <hi rendition="#i">Humboldt.</hi>
                        </hi>
                    </salute>
                </closer>
            </div>
